Assignment 1: Understanding Apache Spark and Distributed Processing

a) Theory
Explain the concept of distributed data processing.
How does Apache Spark improve performance compared to traditional data processing systems? 
Include the role of in-memory computation.
Ans : 
Distributed data processing is the method of breaking down a massive dataset into smaller chunks (partitions) and processing them simultaneously across a cluster of multiple computers (nodes). Instead of one powerful machine struggling with a 1TB file, 10 machines process 100GB each in parallel.

How Spark Improves Performance:
Traditional systems like Hadoop MapReduce were "disk-bound"—they wrote data to the physical hard drive after every single map or reduce step. Spark revolutionizes this through:

In-Memory Computation: Spark stores intermediate data in RAM (Random Access Memory). Since RAM is significantly faster than disk I/O, Spark can be up to 100x faster for iterative algorithms.

DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph): Spark tracks the sequence of operations and creates an optimized execution plan to reduce data shuffling across the network.
